 laws do little to help disadvantaged women. Instead,advocates of safe haven laws target teenagers, women of color, and poor womenwith safe haven information and see relinquishing custody of their newborns asan act of maternal love. Disadvantaged women are preemptively judged as “bad”mothers whose babies would be better off without them.Laury Oaks argues that the labeling of certain kinds ofwomen as potential “bad” mothers who should consider anonymously giving uptheir newborns for adoption into a “loving” home should best be understood asan issue of reproductive justice. Safe haven discourses promote narrow imagesof who deserves to be a mother and reflect restrictive views on how we shouldtreat women experiencing unwanted pregnancy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAbandoned childrenxLegal status, laws, etcxUnited States. 0aAbandoned childrenxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aAbandoned childrenxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aAbandoned childrenxUnited States. 0aAbandoned childrenzUnited States. 0aAdoptionxLaw and legislationxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aAdoptionxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aAdoptionxUnited States. 0aAdoptionzUnited States. 0aBirthmothersxLegal status, laws, etcxUnited States. 0aBirthmothersxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aBirthmothersxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aBirthmothersxUnited States. 0aBirthmotherszUnited States. 7aLAW / Child Advocacy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072899640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479883073423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479883073.jpg  a978-3-11-072899-6  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_C